{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17652179","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17652179"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:33:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:33:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18518"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18518","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18518"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0,0.07,0.22,0.56]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11247"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75367"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11247","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11247"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18518"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60876"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7428"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26070"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26071"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26093"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75367","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75367"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe psoas major muscle is an important postural and locomotor muscle that spans multiple joints.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the anatomical attachments of the psoas major muscle?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["From lumbar vertebrae to ischial tuberosity","From sacrum to pubic tubercle","From thoracic vertebrae to iliac crest","From iliac crest to greater trochanter of femur","From lumbar vertebrae to lesser trochanter of femur"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Epsoas major muscle (image) originates from the lumbar vertebrae and inserts into the lesser trochanter of femur\u003C/strong\u003E. Specifically, it attaches to the transverse processes and vertebral bodies of T12-L5, and joins with the iliacus muscle to form the iliopsoas before inserting into the lesser trochanter.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFrom lumbar vertebrae to ischial tuberosity\u003C/strong\u003E - The ischial tuberosity is an attachment point for hamstring muscles, not the psoas major\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFrom sacrum to pubic tubercle\u003C/strong\u003E - This pathway does not correspond to any major muscle\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFrom thoracic vertebrae to iliac crest\u003C/strong\u003E - This more closely describes parts of the erector spinae muscle group\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFrom iliac crest to greater trochanter of femur\u003C/strong\u003E - These are the attachments of the gluteus medius and minimus muscles\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe psoas major is primarily responsible for hip flexion and assists in lateral flexion of the lumbar spine when contracting unilaterally. It works in conjunction with the iliacus muscle as the iliopsoas complex.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The psoas major muscle originates from T12-L5 vertebrae and inserts into the lesser trochanter of the femur.","The psoas major muscle is a primary hip flexor and weak lumbar spine flexor.","The psoas major muscle forms part of the iliopsoas complex along with the iliacus muscle."],"referenc